TITLE: Creating Complex Runnable Graph with GraphDSL
DESCRIPTION: Demonstrates creating a complex stream processing network with fan-in, fan-out operators and cycles using GraphDSL. The graph is closed (has no unwired ports) and therefore can be materialized.
SOURCE: https://github.com/akka/akka/blob/main/akka-docs/src/main/paradox/stream/stream-composition.md#2025-04-22_snippet_8

LANGUAGE: Scala
CODE:
```
val g = RunnableGraph.fromGraph(GraphDSL.create() { implicit builder: GraphDSL.Builder[NotUsed] =>
  import GraphDSL.Implicits._
  val in = Source(1 to 10)
  val out = Sink.foreach(println)

  val bcast = builder.add(Broadcast[Int](2))
  val merge = builder.add(Merge[Int](2))

  val f1, f2, f3, f4 = Flow[Int].map(_ + 10)

  in ~> f1 ~> bcast ~> f2 ~> merge ~> f3 ~> out
              bcast ~> f4 ~> merge
  ClosedShape
})
```

LANGUAGE: Java
CODE:
```
final RunnableGraph<NotUsed> g =
    RunnableGraph.fromGraph(
        GraphDSL.create(
            builder -> {
              final Source<Integer, NotUsed> in = Source.from(Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 4, 5));
              final Sink<Integer, NotUsed> out = Sink.foreach(System.out::println);

              final UniformFanOutShape<Integer, Integer> bcast = builder.add(Broadcast.create(2));
              final UniformFanInShape<Integer, Integer> merge = builder.add(Merge.create(2));

              final Flow<Integer, Integer, NotUsed> f1 = Flow.of(Integer.class).map(elem -> elem + 10);
              final Flow<Integer, Integer, NotUsed> f2 = Flow.of(Integer.class).map(elem -> elem + 10);
              final Flow<Integer, Integer, NotUsed> f3 = Flow.of(Integer.class).map(elem -> elem + 10);
              final Flow<Integer, Integer, NotUsed> f4 = Flow.of(Integer.class).map(elem -> elem + 10);

              builder
                  .from(in)
                  .via(builder.add(f1))
                  .viaFanOut(bcast)
                  .via(builder.add(f2))
                  .viaFanIn(merge)
                  .via(builder.add(f3))
                  .to(out);
              builder.from(bcast).via(builder.add(f4)).toFanIn(merge);
              return ClosedShape.getInstance();
            }));
```

