TITLE: Creating Nested Akka Streams Components (Java)
DESCRIPTION: Illustrates how to create composite, reusable `Source` and `Sink` components in Java by grouping internal flows using `named()`. This technique hides internal complexity and promotes modularity in stream graph design.
SOURCE: https://github.com/akka/akka/blob/main/akka-docs/src/main/paradox/stream/stream-composition.md#2025-04-22_snippet_5

LANGUAGE: Java
CODE:
```
//##nested-flow
final Source<Integer, NotUsed> nestedSource =
    Source.single(0) // An atomic source
        .map(i -> i + 1) // an atomic processing stage
        .named("nestedSource"); // wrap it in a reusable composite module

final Flow<Integer, Integer, NotUsed> nestedFlow =
    Flow.of(Integer.class)
        .filter(i -> i != 0) // an atomic processing stage
        .map(i -> i - 2) // another atomic processing stage
        .named("nestedFlow"); // wrap it in a reusable composite module

final Sink<Integer, CompletionStage<Integer>> nestedSink =
    nestedFlow
        .toMat(Sink.<Integer>head(), Keep.right()) // wire an atomic sink to the nestedFlow
        .named("nestedSink"); // wrap it the nestedFlow and the atomic Sink in a composite module

// Create a RunnableGraph from the composite modules
final RunnableGraph<CompletionStage<Integer>> runnableGraph =
    nestedSource.toMat(nestedSink, Keep.right());
//##nested-flow
```

