TITLE: Defining an Echo Manager Actor in Java
DESCRIPTION: This Java snippet defines an `EchoManager` actor that listens for incoming TCP connections. Upon receiving a `Tcp.Connected` message, it creates and registers a `SimpleEchoHandler` actor for the connection, ensuring the `keepOpenOnPeerClosed` option is set to true. This allows the handler to finish sending data even if the client half-closes the connection.
SOURCE: https://github.com/akka/akka/blob/main/akka-docs/src/main/paradox/io-tcp.md#2025-04-22_snippet_5

LANGUAGE: java
CODE:
```
public class EchoManager extends AbstractActor {

  private final LoggingAdapter log = Logging.getLogger(getContext().system(), this);
  private final ActorRef listener;

  public EchoManager(ActorRef listener) {
    this.listener = listener;

    // sign death pact: this actor stops when the server stops
    getContext().watch(listener);
  }

  public static Props props(ActorRef listener) {
    return Props.create(EchoManager.class, listener);
  }

  @Override
  public Receive createReceive() {
    return receiveBuilder()
        .match(
            Tcp.Connected.class,
            conn -> {
              log.info("Remote address {} connected", conn.remoteAddress());
              final ActorRef handler = getContext().actorOf(SimpleEchoHandler.props(getSender()));
              getSender().tell(TcpMessage.register(handler, true), getSelf());
            })
        .matchEquals(
            Stop.instance(),
            stop -> {
              log.info("Stopping echo manager");
              listener.tell(TcpMessage.unbind(), getSelf());
              getContext().become(stopping());
            })
        .build();
  }

  private Receive stopping() {
    return receiveBuilder()
        .matchEquals(
            TcpMessage.unbound(),
            unbound -> {
              log.info("Echo manager unbound");
              getContext().stop(getSelf());
            })
        .match(
            CommandFailed.class,
            failed -> {
              // listener already unbound
              getContext().stop(getSelf());
            })
        .build();
  }

  public static final class Stop { // this is the message that the main Actor sends to this actor
    // to initiate the stopping sequence
    public static final Stop instance() {
      return INSTANCE;
    }

    private static final Stop INSTANCE = new Stop();

    private Stop() {}
  }
}

```

