TITLE: Counting Characters per Line using splitAfter in Java
DESCRIPTION: Provides a practical example of using `splitAfter` to process a stream of characters representing text lines. It splits the stream after each newline character, counts the characters in each resulting substream (line), and prints the count.
SOURCE: https://github.com/akka/akka/blob/main/akka-docs/src/main/paradox/stream/stream-substream.md#2025-04-22_snippet_13

LANGUAGE: Java
CODE:
```
//#wordCount
final String text =
    "This is the first line.\n" + "And this is the second line.\n" + "Here is the third line.";

Source.from(Arrays.asList(text.split("")))
    .map(c -> c.charAt(0))
    .splitAfter(c -> c == '\n')
    .filter(c -> c != '\n')
    .map(
        c -> {
          System.out.print(c);
          return 1;
        })
    .reduce((i, acc) -> i + acc)
    .map(
        i -> {
          System.out.println();
          return i;
        })
    .concatSubstreams()
    .runForeach(System.out::println, system);
//#wordCount
```

