TITLE: Merging Partitioned Streams with MergeSequence in Java
DESCRIPTION: This Java example shows how to use MergeSequence with Partition to merge a partitioned stream back into a single ordered stream. It processes even-numbered messages and merges them with unprocessed odd-numbered messages.
SOURCE: https://github.com/akka/akka/blob/main/akka-docs/src/main/paradox/stream/operators/MergeSequence.md#2025-04-22_snippet_1

LANGUAGE: Java
CODE:
```
Source<Pair<String, Integer>> source =
    Source.range(1, 10)
        .map(n -> n % 2 == 0 ? "even " + n : "odd " + n)
        .zipWith(Source.range(0, 100), Pair::new);

Pair<Source<Pair<String, Integer>>, Source<Pair<String, Integer>>> partition =
    source.partition(pair -> pair.first().startsWith("even"), 2);

Source<Pair<String, Integer>> needsProcessing = partition.first();
Source<Pair<String, Integer>> noProcessing = partition.second();

Source<Pair<String, Integer>> processedMessages =
    needsProcessing.map(
        pair -> Pair.create("processed " + pair.first(), pair.second()));

Source<Pair<String, Integer>> mergedSource =
    Source.fromGraph(
        GraphDSL.create(
            builder -> {
              MergeSequence<Pair<String, Integer>> merge =
                  builder.add(MergeSequence.create(2));
              builder.from(processedMessages).toInlet(merge.in(0));
              builder.from(noProcessing).toInlet(merge.in(1));
              return SourceShape.of(merge.out());
            }));

mergedSource.runForeach(System.out::println, system);
```

