TITLE: Managing Pull-Based Connection Accepting in Java
DESCRIPTION: A Java example showing how to handle connection acceptance in pull mode. After processing a new connection, the actor resumes accepting more connections by sending a TcpMessage.resumeAccepting() message.
SOURCE: https://github.com/akka/akka/blob/main/akka-docs/src/main/paradox/io-tcp.md#2025-04-22_snippet_25

LANGUAGE: java
CODE:
```
private final LoggingAdapter log = Logging.getLogger(getContext().getSystem(), this);
private final ActorRef connectionsCounter;
private final Class<?> handlerClass;

@Override
public Receive createReceive() {
  return receiveBuilder()
      .match(
          Tcp.Bound.class,
          msg -> {
            getSender().tell(TcpMessage.resumeAccepting(1), getSelf());
            log.info("Listening on {}", msg.localAddress());
            getContext().become(listening(getSender()));
          })
      .build();
}

private Receive listening(final ActorRef connectionTacker) {
  return receiveBuilder()
      .match(
          Tcp.Connected.class,
          conn -> {
            final ActorRef handler =
                getContext()
                    .actorOf(
                        Props.create(handlerClass, getSender(), conn.remoteAddress(), connectionsCounter));

            getSender().tell(TcpMessage.register(handler, true, true), getSelf());

            // after handling one connection we need to resume accepting again
            connectionTacker.tell(TcpMessage.resumeAccepting(1), getSelf());
          })
      .build();
}
```

