TITLE: Merging Partitioned Streams with MergeSequence in Scala
DESCRIPTION: This example demonstrates how to use MergeSequence in combination with Partition to merge a partitioned stream back into a single stream while maintaining the original element order. It processes messages selectively and then merges them for acknowledgment.
SOURCE: https://github.com/akka/akka/blob/main/akka-docs/src/main/paradox/stream/operators/MergeSequence.md#2025-04-22_snippet_0

LANGUAGE: Scala
CODE:
```
val source = Source(1 to 10)
  .map(n => if (n % 2 == 0) s"even $n" else s"odd $n")
  .zipWithIndex
  .map { case (elem, idx) => (elem, idx.toInt) }

val (needsProcessing, noProcessing) = source.partition(_._1.startsWith("even"), outputArity = 2)

val processedMessages = needsProcessing
  .map { case (msg, idx) => (s"processed $msg", idx) }

Source.fromGraph(
  GraphDSL.create() { implicit b =>
    import GraphDSL.Implicits._
    val merge = b.add(MergeSequence[(String, Int)](outputArity = 2))
    processedMessages ~> merge.in(0)
    noProcessing ~> merge.in(1)
    SourceShape(merge.out)
  }
).runForeach(println)
```

