TITLE: Using Broadcast to Aggregate Stream Values in Java
DESCRIPTION: This Java snippet illustrates using `builder.broadcast(2)` within a `GraphDSL` to split a stream of integers. One output path calculates the sum using `reduce`, while the other calculates the count using `reduce`. The results are then zipped together and printed. It requires importing necessary Akka Streams classes.
SOURCE: https://github.com/akka/akka/blob/main/akka-docs/src/main/paradox/stream/operators/Broadcast.md#2025-04-22_snippet_1

LANGUAGE: java
CODE:
```
import akka.NotUsed;
import akka.stream.*;
import akka.stream.javadsl.*;
import jdocs.AbstractJavaTest;
```

LANGUAGE: java
CODE:
```
final Source<Integer, NotUsed> source = Source.range(1, 10);

final Sink<BigInteger, CompletionStage<BigInteger>> sumSink =
    Sink.<BigInteger, Integer>fold(BigInteger.ZERO, (acc, el) -> acc.add(BigInteger.valueOf(el)));
final Sink<Integer, CompletionStage<Integer>> countSink =
    Sink.<Integer, Integer>fold(0, (acc, el) -> acc + 1);

final RunnableGraph<Pair<CompletionStage<BigInteger>, CompletionStage<Integer>>> graph =
    RunnableGraph.<Pair<CompletionStage<BigInteger>, CompletionStage<Integer>>>fromGraph(
        GraphDSL.create(
            sumSink, // S1
            countSink, // S2
            Keep.both(),
            (builder, s1, s2) -> {
              final UniformFanOutShape<Integer, Integer> broadcast =
                  builder.add(Broadcast.create(2));

              builder.from(builder.add(source)).toFanOut(broadcast);

              builder.from(broadcast.out(0)).via(builder.add(Flow.of(Integer.class).map(BigInteger::valueOf))).to(s1);
              builder.from(broadcast.out(1)).to(s2);
              return ClosedShape.getInstance();
            }));

final Pair<CompletionStage<BigInteger>, CompletionStage<Integer>> result = graph.run(system);

result
    .first()
    .thenAcceptAsync(s -> System.out.println("Sum: " + s), system.dispatcher());
result
    .second()
    .thenAcceptAsync(c -> System.out.println("Count: " + c), system.dispatcher());
```

