TITLE: Illustrating Buffer Abstraction Leak in Akka Streams (Java)
DESCRIPTION: This Java example demonstrates a potential issue where internal buffering affects rate-based operations. The `conflateWithSeed` operator aggregates elements based on downstream demand timed by `ZipWith` and a `TickSource`. Due to the default internal buffer prefetching elements into `ZipWith`, the conflation step receives elements prematurely, leading to an output of '1' instead of the expected '3'. Reducing the buffer size to 1 helps align behavior with expectations.
SOURCE: https://github.com/akka/akka/blob/main/akka-docs/src/main/paradox/stream/stream-rate.md#2025-04-22_snippet_12

LANGUAGE: java
CODE:
```
final Flow<Integer, Integer, NotUsed> flow = Flow.of(Integer.class).map(i -> i);

final Attributes bufferAttr = Attributes.inputBuffer(1, 1);

final RunnableGraph<?> runnableGraph = Source.tick(Duration.ofSeconds(1), Duration.ofSeconds(1), "tick")
    .zipWith(Source.range(1, 10), (tick, i) -> i)
    .via(flow.async())
    .conflateWithSeed(
        i -> {
          System.out.println("first: " + i);
          return i;
        },
        (agg, i) -> {
          System.out.println("agg: " + agg + " -> " + i);
          return agg + i;
        }
    )
    .map(i -> { System.out.println("last: " + i); return i; })
    .zipWith(Source.tick(Duration.ofSeconds(3), Duration.ofSeconds(3), "tick"), (i, tick) -> i)
    // demonstrate the need for controlling buffer sizes
    .withAttributes(bufferAttr)
    .map(i -> { System.out.println("Got: " + i); return i; });

runnableGraph.run(system);
```

