TITLE: Splitting Streams using splitWhen and splitAfter in Java
DESCRIPTION: Compares the `splitWhen` and `splitAfter` operators in Akka Streams. `splitWhen` starts a new substream *with* the element satisfying the predicate, while `splitAfter` starts a new substream *after* the element satisfying the predicate. Both merge the substreams sequentially using `concatSubstreams`.
SOURCE: https://github.com/akka/akka/blob/main/akka-docs/src/main/paradox/stream/stream-substream.md#2025-04-22_snippet_11

LANGUAGE: Java
CODE:
```
//#splitWhenAfter
Source.range(1, 10)
    .splitWhen(i -> i % 3 == 0)
    .map(
        i -> {
          System.out.println("splitWhen: " + i);
          return i;
        })
    .concatSubstreams()
    .runWith(Sink.ignore(), system);

System.out.println("---------------------------");

Source.range(1, 10)
    .splitAfter(i -> i % 3 == 0)
    .map(
        i -> {
          System.out.println("splitAfter: " + i);
          return i;
        })
    .concatSubstreams()
    .runWith(Sink.ignore(), system);
//#splitWhenAfter
```

