TITLE: Changing Actor Behavior in Functional Style (Java)
DESCRIPTION: Illustrates a common functional programming pattern in Akka Typed (Java) where an actor changes its behavior in response to messages (e.g., from `idle` to `workInProgress`) by returning a new behavior instance. This is relevant when applying supervision.
SOURCE: https://github.com/akka/akka/blob/main/akka-docs/src/main/paradox/typed/fault-tolerance.md#2025-04-22_snippet_9

LANGUAGE: java
CODE:
```
// #wrap
static Behavior<String> worker(int inProgress) {
  return Behaviors.receiveMessage(
      (String message) -> {
        if (message.equals("step")) {
          return worker(inProgress + 1);
        } else if (message.equals("reset")) {
          return worker(0);
        } else {
          return Behaviors.unhandled();
        }
      });
}

static Behavior<String> idle() {
  return Behaviors.receiveMessage(
      (String message) -> {
        if (message.equals("step")) {
          return workInProgress(1);
        } else {
          return Behaviors.unhandled();
        }
      });
}

static Behavior<String> workInProgress(int count) {
  return Behaviors.receiveMessage(
      (String message) -> {
        if (message.equals("step")) {
          return workInProgress(count + 1);
        } else if (message.equals("done")) {
          return idle();
        } else {
          return Behaviors.unhandled();
        }
      });
}
// #wrap

```

