TITLE: Implementing Tell Protection Pattern with CircuitBreaker (Java)
DESCRIPTION: This example shows how to implement the Tell Protection pattern using the low-level CircuitBreaker API in Java, manually tracking success and failure for operations that expect replies.
SOURCE: https://github.com/akka/akka/blob/main/akka-docs/src/main/paradox/common/circuitbreaker.md#2025-04-22_snippet_9

LANGUAGE: Java
CODE:
```
static class DangerousJavaActor extends AbstractActor {

  private final CircuitBreaker circuitBreaker;

  public DangerousJavaActor() {
    this.circuitBreaker =
        new CircuitBreaker(
            getContext().getSystem().getScheduler(),
            5,
            Duration.ofSeconds(10),
            Duration.ofMinutes(1));
  }

  @Override
  public Receive createReceive() {
    return receiveBuilder()
        .match(
            String.class,
            message -> {
              if ("is-closed".equals(message)) {
                getSender().tell(circuitBreaker.isClosed(), getSelf());
              } else if ("dangerous-call".equals(message)) {
                if (circuitBreaker.isClosed() || circuitBreaker.isHalfOpen()) {
                  final ActorRef client = getSender();
                  getContext()
                      .getSystem()
                      .getScheduler()
                      .scheduleOnce(
                          Duration.ofSeconds(5),
                          () -> client.tell("call-result", getSelf()),
                          getContext().getDispatcher());

                  // We know that the call succeeded so we tell the circuit breaker
                  circuitBreaker.succeed();
                } else {
                  getSender().tell("circuit-breaker-open", getSelf());
                }
              } else if ("exception-call".equals(message)) {
                if (circuitBreaker.isClosed() || circuitBreaker.isHalfOpen()) {
                  final ActorRef client = getSender();
                  getContext()
                      .getSystem()
                      .getScheduler()
                      .scheduleOnce(
                          Duration.ofSeconds(5),
                          () ->
                              client.tell(
                                  new Status.Failure(new RuntimeException("Bad response")),
                                  getSelf()),
                          getContext().getDispatcher());

                  // We know that the call failed so we tell the circuit breaker
                  circuitBreaker.fail();
                } else {
                  getSender().tell("circuit-breaker-open", getSelf());
                }
              }
            })
        .build();
  }
}
```

