TITLE: Using Request Context with Update in Java
DESCRIPTION: Java example showing how to pass a request context (original sender) with an Update message, which can be used to route the response back to the original requester.
SOURCE: https://github.com/akka/akka/blob/main/akka-docs/src/main/paradox/distributed-data.md#2025-04-22_snippet_9

LANGUAGE: java
CODE:
```
final Key<PNCounter> Counter1Key = PNCounterKey.create("counter1");
replicator.tell(
    new Update<PNCounter>(
        Counter1Key,
        PNCounter.create(),
        WriteLocal.instance(),
        curr -> curr.increment(node, 1),
        getContext().getSender()),
    getSelf());

// handle response
receiveBuilder()
    .match(
        UpdateSuccess.class,
        a -> {
          if (a.key().equals(Counter1Key) && a.getRequest().isPresent()) {
            ActorRef replyTo = (ActorRef) a.getRequest().get();
            replyTo.tell("updated", getSelf());
          }
        })
    .match(
        UpdateTimeout.class,
        a -> {
          if (a.key().equals(Counter1Key) && a.getRequest().isPresent()) {
            ActorRef replyTo = (ActorRef) a.getRequest().get();
            replyTo.tell("not updated, but will eventually be replicated", getSelf());
          }
        })
    .build();
```

