TITLE: Implementing Custom Failure Counting in Akka CircuitBreaker (Java)
DESCRIPTION: This Java example shows how to define custom failure criteria for a circuit breaker by treating even numbers as failures, regardless of whether the operation succeeds or fails.
SOURCE: https://github.com/akka/akka/blob/main/akka-docs/src/main/paradox/common/circuitbreaker.md#2025-04-22_snippet_5

LANGUAGE: Java
CODE:
```
// We define a function that will determine whether to count the result as a failure.
// In this example, we treat even numbers as failure, regardless whether
// the operation succeeded or not
BiFunction<Optional<Object>, Optional<Throwable>, Boolean> defineEvenNumberAsFailure =
    (result, err) -> {
      if (err.isPresent()) return true;
      if (!result.isPresent()) return false;
      if (result.get() instanceof Integer) {
        return ((Integer) result.get()) % 2 == 0;
      }
      return false;
    };

CircuitBreaker circuitBreaker =
    CircuitBreaker.create(
        system.scheduler(),
        1,
        Duration.ofSeconds(1),
        Duration.ofSeconds(1));

// Protect the even-as-failure logic
List<Integer> oddAndEvenNumbers = Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 4, 5);

List<CompletionStage<Integer>> futures =
    oddAndEvenNumbers.stream()
        .map(
            n ->
                circuitBreaker.callWithCircuitBreaker(
                    () -> {
                      try {
                        Thread.sleep(10);
                        return n;
                      } catch (InterruptedException e) {
                        throw new CompletionException(e);
                      }
                    },
                    defineEvenNumberAsFailure))
        .collect(Collectors.toList());
```

